Title: Inception
Summary: One of the greatest movies ever made. The story and the music are the absolute best and something no one could have done as well as Nolan. The scene when Leo DiCaprio gets home and Time by Hans Zimmer is playing makes me cry every time and this score makes any ordinary scene in life look epic. It means more to me than anything because it also played as I landed in Ireland for the first time. The idea of the totem to know if you are in a dream or not and that to be the greatest cliffhanger and mystery in cinematic history leaves me in awe of the genius that flowed into writing this movie.

AdditionalInfo: signed by Linus Sandgren, also available in Farsi
Summary: I am the fool who dreams, so this movie will always be the reason I will not stop dreaming. It came at the exact right time and I will be forever grateful for that. The music is incredibly delicate and beautiful and fitting and just *chef's kiss*. Damien Chazelle hit a nerve with this movie and Emma Stone's monologue in Boulder is what I regularly fall back to and even if I don't have a Ryan Gosling to tell me to get my shit together I think of Sebastian and Mia and how their lives turned out. The story might be fiction but I see my truth in it and moreso, my future. AND of course the DVD is signed beautifully by Linus Sandgren which was one of my favorite interactions with the film industry yet.

Title: The Wild Robot
Summary: A movie that leaves me with tears pouring down my face and questioning if Ratatouille should still be my favorite animated movie of all time. It comes in as a definitive close second and might even overtake it at some point as time passes. The Wild Robot is genuinely one of the most beautiful films I have ever seen both visually and dramaturgically. I can see how it will mean different things to different people and I can definitely see how even I will see different things in the movie as life goes on. This movie is truly art and if it doesn't win the Oscar this year, it will be the second Robot-Animation film in a row to be snubbed for Best Animated Feature.
Cast: Lupita Nyong'o, Pedro Pascal, Kit Connor, Bill Nighy, Stephanie Hsu, Ving Rhames, Mark Hamill, Catherine O'Hara, Matt Berry
